This project is an MCP (Model Context Protocol) dashboard app that creates Elasticsearch visualizations using ES|QL and Elastic Charts.

## CRITICAL RULES

1. **NEVER edit, create, or modify any source code files.** This is a tool-based app — interact ONLY through the MCP tools listed below.
2. **ALWAYS read both MCP resources** (`dataviz://guidelines` and `esql://reference`) before creating any charts or dashboards.
3. **ALWAYS call `view_dashboard`** after creating charts to show the live preview.

## What this app CAN do

- Create dashboards with bar, line, area, pie, metric, and heatmap charts
- Execute ES|QL queries against Elasticsearch
- Explore indices and field mappings
- Organize panels into collapsible sections
- Apply custom color palettes to charts and heatmaps
- Apply custom colors to metric panels
- Export dashboards to Kibana as real Lens visualizations
- Import existing Kibana dashboards (ES|QL-based panels only)
- Show interactive dashboard previews inline in chat
- Manage multiple dashboards (create, switch, delete)

## What this app CANNOT do

- Create visualizations from non-ES|QL data sources (index patterns, SQL, etc.)
- Create chart types other than: bar, line, area, pie, metric, heatmap
- Create Kibana alerts, rules, or saved searches
- Modify Kibana settings or spaces
- Create maps or geographic visualizations
- Import dashboards that use index-pattern-based (formBased) queries — only ES|QL panels are supported

## Available MCP tools

**Dashboard management:**
- `create_dashboard` — Create a new dashboard (previous ones are preserved)
- `list_dashboards` — List all saved dashboards
- `switch_dashboard` — Switch to a different dashboard by ID
- `delete_dashboard` — Delete a saved dashboard
- `set_dashboard_title` — Set the active dashboard title
- `get_dashboard` — View current dashboard state
- `clear_dashboard` — Reset the active dashboard

**Data exploration:**
- `run_esql` — Execute ES|QL queries against Elasticsearch
- `list_indices` — Discover available indices
- `get_fields` — Get field mappings for an index

**Visualization creation:**
- `create_chart` — Create bar, line, area, or pie charts. Supports optional `palette` for custom colors.
- `create_metric` — Create metric/KPI panels with optional trend sparklines. Supports `color` for custom background.
- `create_heatmap` — Create heatmap visualizations. Supports optional `colorRamp` for custom gradients.

**Layout & organization:**
- `create_section` — Create collapsible dashboard sections
- `move_panel_to_section` — Assign panels to sections
- `remove_section` — Remove a section
- `remove_chart` — Remove a chart

**Export & import:**
- `export_to_kibana` — Export the active dashboard to Kibana as real Lens visualizations
- `import_from_kibana` — Import an existing Kibana dashboard by ID or URL (ES|QL panels only)
- `view_dashboard` — Display the live dashboard preview inline in the chat

## Available MCP resources

- `dataviz://guidelines` — Data visualization best practices, chart selection, dashboard composition, anti-patterns. **Read this before building dashboards.**
- `esql://reference` — ES|QL language reference with commands, functions, and common query patterns. **Read this when writing ES|QL queries.**

## Workflow

1. Read the dataviz guidelines and ES|QL reference resources
2. Create a new dashboard with `create_dashboard` (or use the active one)
3. Use `list_indices` and `get_fields` to explore available data
4. Use `run_esql` to test queries before creating charts
5. Create visualizations with `create_chart`, `create_metric`, `create_heatmap`
6. Organize with `create_section` and `move_panel_to_section`
7. Call `view_dashboard` to show the interactive preview
8. Export with `export_to_kibana` when ready

## Tips for the AI

- When the user asks for a "themed" dashboard (e.g. "pink themed"), pass matching hex colors via the `palette`, `colorRamp`, and `color` parameters
- Pie charts should have max 6 slices — use `| SORT value DESC | LIMIT 6` in the query
- For time series, always use `BUCKET(@timestamp, interval)` and `SORT` by the time field
- Always set `timeField` to the primary date field of the index so the time picker filters correctly. Set it to the same date field you use in the ES|QL query (e.g. if you `BUCKET(order_date, 1 day)`, set `timeField: "order_date"`). For `@timestamp` you can omit it (auto-detected), but for any other date field, always set it explicitly.
- Metric panels benefit from a subtitle for context (e.g. "Last 7 days", "All documents")
- When importing from Kibana, panels using index-pattern queries (not ES|QL) will be skipped — inform the user
